## Workflow conventions

{% include 'workflow-conventions.md' %}

## What to populate

The workflow skill template handles SKILL.md structure, so
the four design fields that matter are:

- `files` — every artifact materialize writes (loom shim,
  Python package, schemas, prompt templates, references).
- `cli_surface` — subcommands the main shim exposes
  (typically `ingest`, `next`, `complete`, plus any
  `pipeline <name>` helpers that tool tasks invoke).
- `tasks` — every loom task in dispatch order. Keystone
  tasks (the algorithmic core) get 3-5 sentence descriptions
  covering inputs, outputs, schema, and downstream
  consumption. Boilerplate tasks (parallel fan-outs,
  near-identical comparators) get 1-2 sentences.
- `rationale` — tradeoffs you considered and rejected
  (DAG shape, fan-out factor, determinism, package layout).

`sections` may stay empty — the workflow skill template
supplies standard SKILL.md sections.

## Output construction

Construct `output.yaml` with loom's schema-driven writer.
The writer validates after every assignment.

```bash
LOOM=~/.kiro/skills/home/loom/scripts/loom.sh
WD={{ run.workdir }}

$LOOM output init "$WD" --task design

$LOOM output add "$WD" --task design \
    --set frontmatter.name=demo \
    --set frontmatter.type=workflow \
    --set 'frontmatter.description=...' \
    --set 'files[].path=scripts/demo.sh' \
    --set 'files[-1].purpose=Loom shim.' \
    --set 'files[-1].content_outline=...' \
    --set 'cli_surface[].command=ingest' \
    --set 'cli_surface[-1].args=<args>' \
    --set 'cli_surface[-1].description=Initialise the loom workdir.' \
    --set 'cli_surface[].command=next' \
    --set 'cli_surface[-1].args=<workdir>' \
    --set 'cli_surface[-1].description=Emit ready tasks.' \
    --set 'tasks[].id=entry' --set 'tasks[-1].kind=agent' \
    --set 'tasks[-1].depends_on=[]' \
    --set 'tasks[-1].description=Keystone — reads ... produces ...' \
    --set 'tasks[].id=fan-out-a' --set 'tasks[-1].kind=agent' \
    --set 'tasks[-1].depends_on=[entry]' \
    --set 'tasks[-1].description=...' \
    --set rationale='DAG shape and fan-out tradeoffs...'
```

Syntax: `[]` appends, `[-1]` targets the last appended entry,
`.` nests. Schema violations exit non-zero with the
violating path.
